Description: DraftMix is an online platform allowing fantasy sports enthusiasts to play pickup games against other players for real and virtual money.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, Silicon Valley, West Coast
Full Description: On DraftMix fantasy sports fans can sign up and play pickup games against other players on the site for virtual dollars or for real money . Open games are listed in a lobby, where players can sign up in groups ranging from 4 to 10 players each paying into a prize pool. DraftMix also ponies up a nightly cash prize for a free game as well. When a game is full, players pick their teams from active profession players. Each fantasy manager's team is scored on their players stats in the upcoming "real world" games. Since stats are needed to find the winning team, the time it takes to finish a game varies by sport. Football fantasy games are finished weekly, since all the teams play each Sunday. Basketball can finish a bit faster since teams play daily. The manager with the most points wins the money pot, with 10% of real cash games going to DraftMix. Now all this may sound fine playing fantasy sports for fantasy dollars, but doesn't bringing real money into play amount to internet gambling? No, says co-founder Matt Maroon, who points the the fantasy sports exemption in the [Internet Gambling Prohibition and Enforcement Act](http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h109-4411). The act, which was a big blow to sites like PartyPoker, specifically exempts "participation in any fantasy or simulation sports game or educational game or contest". Fantasy sports is seen as a game of skill and played for a fixed cash prize. Although a quick perusal of the exemption leaves feeling they're at least bending the rules. Also in the realm of fantasy sport startups are [Screaming Sports](http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/screamingsports) and [Fleaflicker](http://www.crunchbase.com/organization/fleaflicker).
Industry Groups: Financial Services, Gaming, Lending and Investments, Sports

Full Description: Skillbound.com is a skill swapping, skill training, cross-training social network. The idea is for people to meet in their local communities, share ideas, training and swap their knowledge.  So for example, one person might teach you how to DJ and someone else might teach you conversational Italian in return.   Alternatively, you could fix someone's car in return they could do your year end accounts. The site is also used to find employment.  The emphasis is always on the skills you possess rather than the formal training and education you have.  For example, someone might be proficient at selling items on Ebay; someone else might have an in-depth, albeit, amateur, knowledge of Greek architecture.  Just because you lack formal education in those skills doesn't mean someone wouldn't hire you as a consultant, lecturer, freelancer or tutor. The ultimate idea is to create a skill swapping platform.
